“The Beauty Within” is a short film following sisters Aaraf (@aarafxadam) and Abrar Adam (@abrawrr) on their journey to find their individuality, voice, and strength. A film by @kanxsuda
✨ We interviewed Aaraf for film release, see link in bio. 🔗  These women embody the power of Black female heroism through their vulnerability and unity. The silent interaction between these sisters showcases the power and perseverance that lies within each of us— the beauty within. The film features ballerinas Sydnie Collins and Audrey Malek performing as guiding fairies, leading the main characters through their journey of self-identity. The audio throughout is a poem written to serve as a reminder that “ Black, Indigenous and women of color must always be present, visible and amplified.” - @aarafxadam

*Credits in the Comments*

Curated by contributing Africa editor @artofetheltawe, we spotlight the captivating work by @xawaashking from the series 'One Day These Names Will Be Ours'⁠
➡️ See the full series on @art.feminist ✨⁠
�⁠
Gouled Abdishakour Ahmed (@xawaashking) is an Addis Ababa based Somali visual artist, stylist, costume designer and writer. Their work explores the themes of memory and belonging through the lens of  self portrait photography and self fashioning.  Their ongoing self portrait series One Day These Names Will Be Ours explores the gaps that exist within formal language in the understanding, and contextualization of gender expressions that exist outside of the binary. Gouled's work deals with the notion of futurity, and is heavily aimed at envisioning new &  equitable aesthetic futures for the Horn (of Africa).⁠
�⁠
@xawaashking has an upcoming debut capsule collection and continues to collaborate widely with talents in his native and beyond.

node.text:
Feminist caught up with Dr. Ayana Elizabeth Johnson(@ayanaeliza), who alongside Dr. Katharine K. Wilkinson (@drkwilkinson) edited National best seller ‘All We Can Save: Truth, Courage and Solutions for the Climate Crisis.’ (@allwecansave) The two climate leaders curated an anthology of writings by 60 women at the forefront of the climate movement who are harnessing truth, courage, and solutions to lead humanity forward.⁠⁠
➡️ Read the full feature via #linkinbio ✨⁠⁠
⁠⁠
‘To change everything, we need everyone,’ is the theme at the heart of All We Can Save. If feminism is a movement based on the liberation of all people, climate change must be a feminist issue. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Q:  WOMEN ARE ONE OF THE MOST VULNERABLE GROUPS IN CLIMATE CHANGE, IN YOUR OPINION WOULD YOU AGREE? IF SO, WHY?⁠⁠
⁠⁠
@ayanaaliza: Luckily, I do not have to rely on my opinion. It is robustly supported by evidence that women are disproportionately more vulnerable to climate change. This is true from New Orleans to Bangladesh. The most concise explanation is that climate change exacerbates existing inequalities, placing the most risk on those who are already vulnerable.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
#FeministForAll

node.text:
BIPOC mental health matters. 💭 by #FeministPartner @shegotthepink

“In writer @quinciwho’s excellent article for @doubleblind_mag , "Is Good Therapy Too Inaccessible to POC," she shares her struggles as a Black woman trying to find a Black female therapist and the further damage done by cultural incompetent white therapists who couldn't identify with her race-based trauma.”

“According to the American Psychologist Association's Center for Workforce Studies, 86 percent of the U.S. psychology workforce is white and only four percent Black. Additionally, @mentalhealthamerica reports that "while the implementation of the Affordable Care Act has helped to close the gap in uninsured individuals," the disparity between Black Americans being insured versus white Americans is still glaring.
Mental illness affects people of all races and yet white folks are disproportionately receiving treatment over communities of color. Mental healthcare should be accessible to all.”

“Here are some organizations working to make therapy more accessible to communities of color, especially Black communities: @thelovelandfoundation @therapyforblackgirls @therapyforblkmen @therapyforlatinx @inclusivetherapists”

〰️
“This illustration was drawn in partnership with @diall.app, a Black and queer-owned app that I am proud to be in collaboration with. One of the support hotlines they provide is specifically designed to provide BIPOC-focused aid through the service @callblackline. BIPOC-focused aid provides assistance, guidance, and support that intentionally works to meet the needs of Black, Indigenous & People of Color (BIPOC) and Queer BIPOC.” @shegotthepink
